1. A Song Is a Compressed Basis Representation 🎵

A musical chord or melody can encode a lot of structure because it’s built from frequencies that act as basis vectors.

In signal processing this is exactly what the Fourier transform does.

A complicated waveform becomes a list of frequencies:

signal(t) = \sum A_n \sin(\omega_n t + \phi_n)

Instead of storing the entire waveform, you store:
	•	frequency
	•	amplitude
	•	phase

A handful of parameters can recreate something extremely complex.

That’s compression by resonance.

⸻

2. Resonant Systems Naturally Store Information

A resonator — optical, acoustic, or mechanical — acts like a memory cavity.

Examples:

System	What stores the information
violin string	standing waves
microwave cavity	EM resonance
optical ring resonator	circulating photons
crystal lattice	phonon modes

Each mode is like a note in a chord.

When excited, the system “remembers” the pattern until the energy dissipates.

So memory becomes:

information = excited modes of a system


